04798nam a22007815i 9780823284597DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20192019nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232845977 a10.1515/97808232845972doi  a(DE-B1597)555472  a(OCoLC)1090539877  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPHI0120002bisacsh04a189/.42231 aLaZella, Andrew T., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Singular Voice of Being :bJohn Duns Scotus and Ultimate Difference /cAndrew T. LaZella; ed. by Gyula Klima. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMedieval Philosophy: Texts and Studies00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction: Solomon’s difficulty -- tPart one. Being and ultimate difference -- tChapter one. Being is said in many ways -- tChapter two. The real concept of being -- tChapter three. Ultimate difference -- tPart two. Regions of ultimate difference -- tChapter four. The first cut—the intrinsic modes of being -- tChapter five. Ultimate specific differences -- tChapter six. Haecceitas, or naked singularity -- tConclusion: I wouldn’t know him from Adam -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Singular Voice of Being reconsiders John Duns Scotus’s well-studied theory of the univocity of being in light of his less explored discussions of ultimate difference. Ultimate difference is a notion introduced by Aristotle and known by the Aristotelian tradition, but one that, this book argues, Scotus radically retrofits to buttress his doctrine of univocity. Scotus broadens ultimate difference to include not only specific differences, but also intrinsic modes of being (e.g., finite/infinite) and principles of individuation (i.e., haecceitates). Furthermore, he deepens it by divorcing it from anything with categorical classification, such as substantial form. Scotus uses his revamped notion of ultimate difference as a means of dividing being, despite the longstanding Parmenidean arguments against such division. The book highlights the unique role of difference in Scotus’s thought, which conceives of difference not as a fall from the perfect unity of being but rather as a perfective determination of an otherwise indifferent concept. The division of being culminates in individuation as the final degree of perfection, which constitutes indivisible (i.e., singular) degrees of being. This systematic study of ultimate difference opens new dimensions for understanding Scotus’s dense thought with respect to not only univocity, but also to individuation, cognition, and acts of the will.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 4aMedieval Studies. 4aPhilosophy & Theory. 4aTheology. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Medieval.2bisacsh  aAnalogy.  aBeing.  aDifference.  aHaecceity (Haecceitas).  aJohn Duns Scotus.  aMedieval Philosophy.  aMetaphysics.  aUnivocity.1 aKlima, Gyula, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311072273440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823284597zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823284597423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823284597/original  a978-3-11-072273-4  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  